__linux__ and __GLIBC__: These preprocessor symbols control which #if/#else block is compiled. To determine whether either the first or the second block is actually present in the translation unit (and thus whether any branch in the function is compile-time unreachable) you must know whether these macros are defined for the build.

mhd_tool_get_proc_cpu_count_sched_getaffinity_: The function is called first (or second) and its return value controls early returns. You must inspect its declaration/definition to see if it is a macro/inline that unconditionally returns a positive value, marked noreturn, or otherwise guaranteed to force a return (which would make subsequent calls/statements in this function unreachable).

mhd_tool_get_proc_cpu_count_cpuset_getaffinity_: Same reasoning as above: its implementation may unconditionally return >0, be a macro, be compiled out on some platforms, or be noreturn — any of which affects reachability of code that follows it in this function.

mhd_tool_get_proc_cpu_count_sched_getaffinity_np_: This fallback is invoked after the two platform-specific attempts; its implementation/attributes determine whether later code (the w32 call and final return -1) can ever execute.

mhd_tool_get_proc_cpu_count_w32_: This Windows-specific attempt is called unconditionally in source after the affinity calls. You must examine its definition (or conditional compilation around it) to know whether it is present in the build and whether it can force an early return (or always succeed), any of which would make subsequent code unreachable.

In short: to decide if any source statements inside mhd_tool_get_proc_cpu_count are unreachable you need the build-time definitions of the platform macros and the actual declarations/definitions (or macros/attributes) of each callee to know whether they are compiled in and whether they can deterministically prevent reaching later statements.
